===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
There were 5 forms of {{lang|zh|卒}} in Shang oracle bone script ({{zh-ref|Qiu, 1990}}; {{zh-ref|Xuan, 2012}}):
# [[File:卒-oracle-2.svg|30px]]: same as {{zh-l|*衣|clothes}} (> Western Zhou bronze script [[File:卒-bronze.svg|30px]]);
# [[File:卒-oracle-3.svg|30px]]: a crisscross {{zh-l|*衣}} - a completed clothing;
# [[File:卒-oracle.svg|30px]] ({{lang|zh|卒}}): {{liushu|ic|nocap=y}}: {{zh-l|*衣|clothes}} with a mark - a completed clothing to be folded (> Warring States bronze script [[File:卒-bronze-warring.svg|30px]]; Chu slip and silk script [[File:卒-silk.svg|30px]]);
# [[File:𧙻-oracle.svg|30px]] ({{zh-l|*𧙻}}): {{liushu|psc|nocap=y}}: {{zh-l|*衣|clothes}} + {{och-l|聿}} (hand ({{zh-l|*又}}) holding a brush);
# [[File:𧙻-oracle-3.svg|30px]],[[File:𧙻-oracle-2.svg|30px]]: {{lang|zh|𧙻}} having {{lang|zh|又}} omitted.
The brush shape in form (5) was often placed upside down. Later the inverted brush shape was mistaken as {{lang|zh|又}} and then moved to the top as in Chu slip and silk script [[File:𰠄-silk.svg|30px]] ({{zh-l|*𰠄}}) to avoid obscuration with {{zh-l|*袁}} ({{lang|zh|衣}} + {{lang|zh|又}}) ({{zh-ref|Xuan, 2012}}).

===Etymology 1===
From {{och-l|遭|to meet}} + nominal suffix ''*-t'' ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

